data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` |

Here's the converted code:

```csharp
// Shared one-time setup/teardown via a fixture class
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

// IClassFixture<T> triggers the shared fixture lifecycle
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        // Constructor runs before each test (SetUp)
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Runs after each test (TearDown)
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test** setup → constructor; teardown → `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **Per-class** (one-time) setup → `IClassFixture<T>` with a fixture class that itself implements `IDisposable` for teardown
- If you need to share state across **multiple test classes**, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead
